---
description: One responsibility per function; extract helpers when logic grows
alwaysApply: true
---

# Single Responsibility

Each function should do one thing. When a function handles validation, transformation, and side effects together, extract auxiliary functions.

- ✅ Good:

  ```typescript
  const isValidEmail = (email: string) => /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/.test(email)

  const normalizeEmail = (email: string) => email.trim().toLowerCase()

  export const parseUserEmail = (email: string) => {
    const normalized = normalizeEmail(email)
    if (!isValidEmail(normalized)) return null

    return normalized
  }
  ```

- ❌ Bad:

  ```typescript
  export const parseUserEmail = (email: string) => {
    const trimmed = email.trim().toLowerCase()
    const isValid = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/.test(trimmed)
    if (!isValid) return null

    // also fetches user, updates cache, and logs — too many responsibilities
    const user = await fetchUserByEmail(trimmed)
    cache.set(trimmed, user)
    logger.info('parsed email', trimmed)

    return trimmed
  }
  ```

### When to extract

- The function name needs "and" to describe what it does
- Multiple levels of nesting that each represent a distinct step
- Reusable logic that could be tested in isolation
- Mixed concerns: I/O, formatting, validation, or UI updates in the same function
